{
  "text": "A non-randomized immunogenicity study in the UK comparing a 2 + 1-and 3 + 1-dose schedule showed no consistent distinct differences between both vaccine schedules as measured by geo- metric mean concentrations (GMC) per vaccine serotype [CITATION_1] . In a recent immunogenicity study in Iceland, post-primary differences in IgG GMCs were found for several serotypes following 2 or 3 primary vaccinations, yet after the booster dose the only difference observed was for serotype 18C [CITATION_2] . However, since both the UK and Iceland study were performed with experimental 9-valent CRM197-conjugated pneumococcal vaccines that may have different immunogenic capacity compared with the currently licensed PCV-7, potential differences between a 2 + 1-and 3 + 1-dose schedule may have been masked [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In 2005, in a single cohort of infants receiving a 2 + 1 PCV-7 schedule, Kaythy et al. demonstrated low pre-booster levels for serotypes 6B and 23F [CITATION_5] . Following the booster vaccination however, no differences were seen.",
  "citation_candidates": [
